<figure class="transmission-figure">
  <figcaption>Climate change as a flow-stock chain (Lecture 12)</figcaption>
  <div class="flow-grid">
    <article>
      <h3>1) Emissions (Flow)</h3>
      <p>Production and consumption create greenhouse gas emissions each period.</p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>2) Atmosphere (Stock)</h3>
      <p>Flows accumulate into a stock; location of origin does not matter for the global stock.</p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>3) Warming</h3>
      <p>The stock traps heat, raising global temperatures with long lags and uncertainty.</p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>4) Impacts</h3>
      <p>Climate change affects welfare through many channels (water, storms, droughts, sea-level rise).</p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>5) Policy Problem</h3>
      <p>Control the flow to manage the stock, under uncertainty, discounting, and global coordination constraints.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</figure>
